(112, 1, '2014-11-17 00:43:18', '2014-11-16 13:43:18', '<h3><strong>What’s your Goal?</strong></h3>\r\n<img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-906" src="http://easyplan.com.au.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/12095907/refinance-293x197.jpg" alt="refinance" width="293" height="197" />\r\n\r\nBefore you decide on whether refinancing is for you, look at why you’re trying to refinance. Are you trying to save money? Do you have multiple loans and are struggling with all of them at once? Let’s take a look at some of the benefits of refinancing.\r\n\r\n<strong>Reducing interest</strong>\r\n\r\nOne of the most common reasons for refinancing is to lower your interest rate. The new rule of thumb is if you can save 1% off your interest rate, you should be looking to refinance.\r\n\r\n<strong>Adjusting your loan term </strong>\r\n\r\nWith fluctuating interest rates, you can save thousands of dollars in interest repayments by changing your loan term drastically without affecting your monthly repayments. This can get you to home owner faster than expected. Beware of hidden costs and charges.\r\n\r\n<strong>Debt Consolidation</strong>\r\n\r\nRefinancing to consolidate your debt can be a good idea at face value, but beware the trap that most homeowners fall into by just continuing their spending which got them into debt initially.\r\n\r\nA common use of debt consolidation is to combine a home equity loan with your mortgage. There can be issues with this and it’s best to talk to a mortgage or finance advisor to understand your options\r\n<h3><strong>When to Refinance</strong></h3>\r\nOnce you know why you’re thinking to refinance, you need to consider the timing and your financial circumstances.\r\n\r\nIf you need to lower the monthly mortgage repayments, it’s definitely a good time to be looking to refinance.\r\n\r\nThis can often extend the length of your loan, so to see if you save, you need to calculate the interest savings in 2 situations:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>New loan has the same term as the old loan</li>\r\n	<li>New loan is the length of your planned refinance</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nTo see if refinancing is in your favour, compare the interest savings and see what comes out on top.\r\n<h3><strong>When not to Refinance</strong></h3>\r\nConsider how long you’re going to be in your house. Factor in your projected savings vs. the cost of refinancing, and figure out how long it will take to cover the initial costs. If it takes 24 months, and you’re planning on selling the house in 1 year, it wouldn’t make sense to refinance.\r\n<h3><strong>The Bottom Line</strong></h3>\r\nIf you’re looking to refinance to save money, keep an eye out on the interest rate. If it starts dropping, start crunching some numbers and see if you’ll be saving money in the long term. If you’re unsure of what to look at, talk to the experts at EasyPlan. There are hidden costs that differ from bank to bank, so invest a little time into talking to an expert – you could be saving a lot of money.', 'Should you refinance?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'should-you-refinance', '', '', '2014-12-12 10:15:40', '2014-12-11 23:15:40', '', 0, 'http://easyplan.com.au/?p=112', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(113, 1, '2014-11-17 00:43:18', '2014-11-16 13:43:18', 'Money is one of those subjects that make people uncomfortable. A US survey by Wells Fargo<!--more-->&amp; Co found that money was the number one topic to make people uneasy, ratinghigher than death, religion and politics.\r\n\r\nExperts suggest that we are doing ourselves a disservice. By not being honest about our spending, we may be putting the household in financial jeopardy; by not openly talking to our ageing parents, we may never learn about their estate wishes.\r\n\r\nWhen we do speak about money we are not always honest. A survey by Realestate.com.au shows that about 4% of buyers will say they paid more for their property than they did, and 5% will say they paid less.\r\n\r\nBehavioural finance expert and head of IncBlot Organisational Psychology, Daniel Crosby, comments that ‘money is shorthand for happiness, power and personal efficacy. When money is short, it can be seen as a deficiency on the part of the breadwinner, and when there is lots of money, there can be fears that greed takes the place of genuine love’.\r\n\r\nFinancial experts stress the need to speak with children about money. Last year the Canadian Foundation for Economic Education (CFEE) launched an annual ‘Talk With Our Kids About Money Day’. CFEE President, Gary Rabbior, comments that ‘we have a responsibility to the next generation to make sure they are better prepared for their money decisions and challenges than past generations’.\r\n\r\nConcerns are similar in Australia. Research by the Commonwealth Bank Foundation indicates that 70% of secondary school teachers are concerned about their students’ financial knowledge.', 'News Article 02', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '112-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-11-17 00:43:18', '2014-11-16 13:43:18', '', 112, 'http://easyplan.com.au/112-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(114, 1, '2014-11-17 00:44:07', '2014-11-16 13:44:07', 'If you’re looking to build your dream home, or just touch up one room, like your kitchen or bedroom, don’t let your finances crush your ideas before they have a chance to shine. Take a look at what you need to consider before you start to renovate.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignleft wp-image-907 size-medium" src="http://easyplan.com.au.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/12095910/renovations-293x197.jpg" alt="renovations" width="293" height="197" />\r\n<h3><strong>Planning and Design</strong></h3>\r\nBefore you start renovating, think of how you live. Do you like to have friends and family over? Are you ok with cleaning? Are you noisy? How you answer these questions will change your layout, but also the colour schemes and even surfaces.\r\n\r\nThings you need to do before you start planning your renovations are:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Assess your current home</li>\r\n	<li>What do you want your renovation to achieve</li>\r\n	<li>Requirements and permits</li>\r\n	<li>Find an architect</li>\r\n	<li>Find a builder</li>\r\n	<li>Have your finances sorted</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Quotes and Budget</strong></h3>\r\nShop around. Quotes are just that – quotes. They aren’t an iron clad contract. There are plenty of calculators online to help you get an initial estimate.\r\n\r\nSome of the costs you’ll need to budget for are:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Building inspectors</li>\r\n	<li>Architects</li>\r\n	<li>Builders</li>\r\n	<li>Electricians</li>\r\n	<li>Plumbers</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>DIY or professional</strong></h3>\r\nIf you know what you are doing, you can look to cut costs by doing some of the work yourself. If you’re experience is watching the Block every week, be wary, as it’s a lot harder than it looks, and doing a bad job can be worse than doing nothing at all.\r\n<h3><strong>Long-term savings</strong></h3>\r\nBefore cutting out items from your renovation due to budget, factor in how it will affect the long term value of the renovation. Things such as solar panels, double brick insulation and even your windows might cost you more initially, but will pay back themselves quickly, and will increase the sale value of your house.', 'Home Renovation : Things to consider', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'home-renovation-things-to-consider', '', '', '2014-12-12 10:12:14', '2014-12-11 23:12:14', '', 0, 'http://easyplan.com.au/?p=114', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(115, 1, '2014-11-17 00:44:07', '2014-11-16 13:44:07', 'Money is one of those subjects that make people uncomfortable. A US survey by Wells Fargo<!--more-->&amp; Co found that money was the number one topic to make people uneasy, ratinghigher than death, religion and politics.\r\n\r\nExperts suggest that we are doing ourselves a disservice. By not being honest about our spending, we may be putting the household in financial jeopardy; by not openly talking to our ageing parents, we may never learn about their estate wishes.\r\n\r\nWhen we do speak about money we are not always honest. A survey by Realestate.com.au shows that about 4% of buyers will say they paid more for their property than they did, and 5% will say they paid less.\r\n\r\nBehavioural finance expert and head of IncBlot Organisational Psychology, Daniel Crosby, comments that ‘money is shorthand for happiness, power and personal efficacy. When money is short, it can be seen as a deficiency on the part of the breadwinner, and when there is lots of money, there can be fears that greed takes the place of genuine love’.\r\n\r\nFinancial experts stress the need to speak with children about money. Last year the Canadian Foundation for Economic Education (CFEE) launched an annual ‘Talk With Our Kids About Money Day’. CFEE President, Gary Rabbior, comments that ‘we have a responsibility to the next generation to make sure they are better prepared for their money decisions and challenges than past generations’.\r\n\r\nConcerns are similar in Australia. Research by the Commonwealth Bank Foundation indicates that 70% of secondary school teachers are concerned about their students’ financial knowledge.', 'News Article 03', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '114-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-11-17 00:44:07', '2014-11-16 13:44:07', '', 114, 'http://easyplan.com.au/114-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(116, 1, '2014-11-17 00:44:23', '2014-11-16 13:44:23', 'What’s the difference between a first-time investor and a seasoned expert? Let’s take a look at a few common mistakes first-timers make and how to avoid them.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignleft wp-image-904 size-medium" src="http://easyplan.com.au.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/16134423/exp-vs-inexp-investors-293x197.jpg" alt="exp-vs-inexp-investors" width="293" height="197" />\r\n<h3>Managing finances</h3>\r\nGetting your finances sorted before you make an offer is critical. Experienced investors know their limits and don’t go over them. Getting the wrong mortgage can be a lifetime mistake if you choose the wrong options or receive bad advice. An EasyPlan expert can help you avoid any pitfalls, but make sure you get help <strong>before </strong>you sign anything.\r\n\r\n<strong>Beginners</strong>: Have a rough idea of their finances, then offer, then organise their finance’s.\r\n\r\n<strong>Experts</strong>: Get pre-approved finance and <strong>only</strong> look for things in their budget.\r\n<h3><strong>\r\nGetting advice</strong></h3>\r\nThere are plenty of people making money on the property market. A lot of them at someone else’s expense. Don’t be that someone else, do your research and don’t just take the advice of one person.\r\n\r\n<strong>Beginners</strong>: Get advice from a friend, check a few things and figure everything else out on the fly.\r\n\r\n<strong>Experts</strong>: Get a recommendation, research, research, research and checks with their accountant and financial planners.\r\n<h3><strong>\r\nManaging your cashflow</strong></h3>\r\nShock horror – banks will lend you more money than you’re able to actually repay. Know what you’re able to repay, and realise that financial circumstances change\r\n\r\n<strong>Beginners</strong>: Have enough money month to month, spend money while maintaining a short buffer.\r\n\r\n<strong>Experts</strong>: Have a cash buffer, income protection insurance, building and contents insurance and landlord insurance.\r\n<h3><strong>\r\nSelling</strong></h3>\r\nProperty is a long term game. There will be ebbs and flows to the property market and your investment where your growth may be stagnant or even go backwards.\r\n\r\n<strong>Beginners</strong>: Gets nervous when there is a bad month or two and looks to sell.\r\n\r\n<strong>Experts</strong>: Has money set aside if things go awry. Ready to wait out the bad periods.\r\n<h3><strong>\r\nSelecting a Location</strong></h3>\r\nLocation, location, location. Perhaps the three most annoying words any potential investor can ever hear. The cliché is used for a reason, however, as it’s one of the most important factors for investment.\r\n\r\nThings to look out for are proximity to school, public transport, shops and parks. Investigate into any planned developments that may affect the previous factors, or that may affect the roads, noise, etc. Even the crime rate can affect the growth of the investment.\r\n\r\n<strong>Beginners</strong>: Buy somewhere close by so they can keep an eye on things.\r\n\r\n<strong>Experts</strong>: Looks all around the country. Property managers can look after the investment.', 'First-time property investors vs experienced property investors', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'first-time-property-investors-vs-experienced-property-investors', '', '', '2014-12-12 10:13:00', '2014-12-11 23:13:00', '', 0, 'http://easyplan.com.au/?p=116', 0, 'post', '', 0),
