(480, 1, '2014-11-26 14:52:51', '2014-11-26 03:52:51', '<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-479" src="http://easyplan.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/fixed-rate-loan-war-197x197.jpg" alt="fixed rate loan war" width="197" height="197" />\r\n\r\nLenders are competing for customers in a fixed-rate loan war that has seen the five year fixed-rate drop below 5% for the first time in over a century of lending by the Commonwealth Bank.\r\n\r\nWith the average five year fixed-rate mortgage sitting at around 5.7%, a loan offering a rate of 4.99% will equate to considerable savings over a five year period; depending, of course, on the movement of variable interest rates.\r\n\r\nUsually a fall in the fixed-rate loan market is indicative of an impending fall in the variable loan market. However, in this instance industry experts cite market competition as the impetus for the lowering of fixed-rate loans. At a time when switching banks is easy, lenders are keen to lock customers into fixed-term loans to secure their customer base.\r\n\r\nDespite this fixed-rate push, Australians prefer variable interest loans.  Figures from the Australian Bureau of Statistics show that, over the past two decades, only about 12% of home loans have been fixed. The figure reached a high during the global financial crises when just over a quarter of all loans were fixed; this has fallen back to approximately 14% of loans (May 2014).\r\n\r\nThe fixed-rate market in Australia is considerably different to some overseas markets. In the United States the bulk of the market secures loans fixed for a period of 20-30 years and, unlike Australia, there are few penalties for breaking the loan or paying the loan off early.\r\n\r\nThe current competition between lenders makes this an excellent time to lock-in a fixed-rate loan. Borrowers, however, are encouraged to do their research. Many fixed loans have penalties for early payment and limit the extra payments that can be made.', 'Customers Win in Fixed-Rate Loan War', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '56-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-11-26 14:52:51', '2014-11-26 03:52:51', '', 56, 'http://easyplan.com.au/56-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
